<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Reports on NATO Summit </TI></H3>
<H4>   U.S. Stance Noted </H4>
<F P=102> OW0701055294 Beijing XINHUA in English 0504 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0701055294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["U.S. Tries To Soothe States Eager To Join NATO"] </F>
  [Text] Washington, January 6 (XINHUA) -- Two days before 
Bill Clinton's first presidential tour of Europe, the United 
States is drumming up its "partnership for peace" program, a 
go-slow plan for the enlargement of the North Atlantic Treaty 
Organization (NATO). 
  Washington has refused to extend immediately the 16-nation 
Transatlantic alliance's security umbrella to Central and 
Eastern European nations, but offered verbal solace instead. 
  "The security of the states that lie between Western Europe 
and Russia affects the security of America," said Vice President 
Al Gore in a speech today at the Institute of World Affairs in 
Milwaukee, Wisconsin. 
  But words are far from formal and quick membership in NATO 
that countries such as Poland, Hungary, the Czech and Slovak 
Republics are desperately seeking. 
  Washington's "partnership for peace" proposal, which Clinton 
will formally present to the NATO summit next week in Brussels, 
Belgium, only gives the applicants a "junior membership." 
  Under the U.S. plan, any Central and Eastern European 
nation, 
including republics of the former Soviet Union, can become a 
"partner for peace" in NATO and participate in military training 
and political cooperation. 
  Polish President Lech Walesa described the Washington 
proposal as "short-sighted and irresponsible." The criticism 
was echoed by other Eastern European leaders. 
  It is unclear whether John Shalikashvili, chairman of the 
U.S. Joint Chiefs of Staff, and Madeleine Albright, Washington's 
ambassador to the U.N., will be able to convince the leaders 
when they visit the area, starting today. 
  Shalikashvili and Albright will join Clinton in Prague next 
week in meetings with leaders of the Czech Republic, Poland, 
Hungary and the Slovak Republic. 
  Clinton had planned to deliver the Milwaukee speech himself, 
but his 70-year-old mother's death earlier today prompted the 
change. 
  However, he will depart for Europe Saturday [8 January] 
night 
as scheduled. 
  This will be one of his three planned trips to Europe this 
year. The other two occasions are the celebration of the 50th 
anniversary of D-Day in the Second World War in France and the 
Group of Seven's annual economic summit in Italy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

