<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Reports on NATO Summit </TI></H3>
<H4>   UK Spokeman Comments </H4>
<F P=102> OW0801020994 Beijing XINHUA in English 0113 GMT 8 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0801020994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] London, January 7 (XINHUA) -- British Prime Minister 
John Major will be meeting U.S. President Bill Clinton in 
Washington in some weeks' time, Major's spokesman announced 
today. 
  The time for Major's second trip to Washington since last 
February has not been set, the spokesman said. 
  However, Major will hold informal talks with Clinton during 
the summit of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) in 
Brussels to be held on January 10-11, the spokesman added. 
There, Major will also meet with French Prime Minister Edouard 
Balladur and Italian Prime Minister Carlo Ciampi. 
  The spokesman said the NATO leaders will make important 
decisions, which will guide NATO's future policy, on: 
  How to develop its relations with Russia, Ukraine and 
countries of Central and Eastern Europe; 
  How to adapt itself in both political and military spheres 
to 
be better able to perform peacekeeping and other peace-support 
missions; 
  And how to accommodate a European defense policy with a 
continuing, viable and "to us extremely important" Transatlantic 
alliance. 

</TEXT>

