<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, January 10 (XINHUA) -- Ukrainian President 
Leonid Kravchuk will come here Friday [14 January] for a meeting 
with visiting U.S. President Bill Clinton and Russian President 
Boris Yeltsin, the presidential press service confirmed today. 
  Yeltsin has formally invited Kravchuk to participate in his 
talks with Clinton, the press service said, adding that this has 
been made possible after the three countries reached an 
understanding on some major issues, including nuclear 
disarmament in Ukraine. 
  However, the Ukrainian president's foreign policy adviser 
Anton Butekyo said earlier on Monday that Kravchuk had not 
decided whether to attend the Moscow summit. 
  Ukraine is the world's third largest nuclear power with some 
1,600 of nuclear war-heads inherited from the former Soviet 
Union. 
  Russia and the United States have been concerned over the 
safety of the nuclear arsenal on the Ukrainian territory. 
  Two days before the trilateral Moscow summit, chairman of 
the 
Belarus Supreme Soviet Stanislav Shushkevich will come for a 
one-on- one meeting with Yeltsin. The talk will focus on the 
nuclear weapons in Belarus, INTERFAX reported. 
  Nuclear issue will also be high on the agenda when President 
Clinton makes a stop-over in Minsk on January 15-16 after the 
NATO summit and his visit to Moscow. 

</TEXT>

