<H3> <TI>   Li Peiyao Meets With U.S. Senator John Kerry </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1101104794 Beijing XINHUA in English 1021 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1101104794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, January 11 (XINHUA) -- Li Peiyao, 
vice-chairman of the Standing Committee of the National People's 
Congress (NPC) of China, met with Senator John F. Kerry, member 
of the U.S. Senate Foreign Affairs Committee, and his party here 
this afternoon. 
  The two sides exchanged views on topics of common interest. 
  Li noted that as two influential countries on the Pacific 
Rim, China and the U.S. share many common interests and their 
economies are highly complementary. 
  The two countries should keep their eyes on the future and 
intensify their cooperation on the principle of seeking common 
ground while laying aside differences, Li said, adding that this 
is in the fundamental interests of the two peoples and conducive 
to world peace and development. 
  Kerry noted that he was pleased to be here and hoped to see 
bilateral ties improved. 
  After the meeting, Zhu Qizhen, vice-chairman of the NPC's 
Foreign Affairs Committee, held working talks with Kerry and his 
party. 
  Also this afternoon, Wu Yi, Chinese minister of foreign 
trade 
and economic cooperation, met with the U.S. visitors. 
  Kerry and his party arrived here on Monday [10 January] as 
guests of the NPC's Foreign Affairs Committee. 

</TEXT>

