<F P=100> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> East Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shanghai Bank Opens to Individuals </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1001135594 Beijing XINHUA in English 1250 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1001135594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, January 10 (XINHUA) -- The Shanghai-based 
Bank of Communications has taken the lead in extending foreign 
exchange business among city residents, international business 
reported. 
  The local branch of the bank, starting the service on 
December 28, 1993, anchored a total transaction of 500,000 U.S. 
dollars through new year's eve. Resuming on January 4, the 
trading is running smoothly. 
  For each transaction, 300 U.S. dollars or an equal amount of 
other foreign currencies is required. The trading hall is well- 
equipped with a computerized quotation, trading and clearing 
system, flashing the latest exchange rates. 
  Through free trading, clients can make money not only from 
interest differentials, but also from exchange fluctuations. 
  Now Shanghainese have found a way to apply foreign exchange 
in hand, besides depositing the money in the bank. 
  Foreign exchange deposits made by Shanghai citizens are on 
the rise. Figures show that the city had more than one million 
depositors by last February, with foreign exchange totalling 1.3 
billion U.S. dollars. 
  Major sources of the money are Shanghai citizens residing 
overseas and businessmen and students based abroad. 

</TEXT>

