<F P=100> Near East &amp; South Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   CPC Central Committee Delegation Visits India </TI></H3>
<H4>   Received by Prime Minister </H4>
<F P=102> OW1101130694 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 1449 
GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW1101130694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] New Delhi, 10 Jan (XINHUA) -- Speaking at a meeting 
with Wen Jiabao, alternate member of the Political Bureau and 
member of the Secretariat of the CPC Central Committee, Indian 
Prime Minister Rao said today that India hoped to speed up the 
process of Sino-Indian cooperation in all spheres. 
  Rao said: The potential for close Sino-Indian cooperation is 
enormous; the prospects for cooperation in agriculture, 
industry, and joint ventures are broad; and speeding up the 
cooperation process will benefit the two countries significantly. 
  Wen Jiabao said, at the meeting, that China and India share 
identical views on many major issues. He expressed appreciation 
for Rao's efforts and contributions to promoting Sino-Indian 
friendship and cooperation. 
  Recalling his visit to China in September last year, Rao 
said 
that his visit opened a new chapter for the two countries' 
relations which have developed in the economic, diplomatic, and 
cultural fields. Commenting about Sino-Indian accord on 
maintaining peace and tranquility along areas under the two 
countries' actual control, Wen Jiabao said that the accord has 
further strengthened Sino-Indian relations and the two countries 
should continue to solidify the existing relations. 
  On strengthening the ties between the CPC and the Indian 
Congress Party, Wen Jiabao said: Since the two parties are 
ruling parties of the two most populous countries in the world, 
China attaches great importance to developing the relations 
between the two parties. The development of the two parties' 
relations will help strengthen the friendship between the their 
leaders as well friendship and cooperation between the peoples 
of the two countries. 
  Wen Jiabao also relayed to Rao cordial regards and best 
wishes from General Secretary Jiang Zemin and Premier Li Peng. 
Rao again invited Jiang Zemin to visit India. He said: "People 
of all walks of life in India are looking forward to President 
Jiang's early visit." 
  During a meeting with Indian Minister of Home Affairs Chavan 
today, Wen Jiabao briefed him on the development of the 
socialist market economy in China. 
  The CPC delegation headed by Wen Jiabao arrived here on 7 
January on a friendly visit to India. 

</TEXT>

