<F P=100> West Europe </F>
<H3> <TI>   French Prime Minister May Visit in January </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK1101053094 Hong Kong AFP in English 0521 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> HK1101053094 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, Jan 11 (AFP) -- A French government 
emissary secretly traveled to Beijing in late December to 
discuss the possibility of a visit by Prime Minister Edouard 
Balladur on the 30th anniversary of the establishment of 
Franco-Chinese diplomatic ties, a reliable sources said here 
Tuesday. 
  Jacques Friedmann, a close associate of Balladur, reportedly 
discussed the plan with representatives of the Chinese 
government. France recognized China in January 27, 1964. 
According to well- informed sources in Beijing, the head of the 
French government would visit China with Foreign Affairs 
Minister Alain Juppe and Industry Minister Gerard Longuet from 
January 27 to 30. 
  Friedmann initially visited Beijing in July to revive the 
dialogue between the two countries, which had halted with the 
sale one year ago of French Mirage 2000-5 aircraft to Taiwan, 
the Nationalist island claimed by China. 
  The high-level visit would open a new chapter in Sino-French 
relations. The sale of warplanes to Taiwan had led to the 
closure of the French consulate in the southern Chinese city of 
Guangzhou and the exclusion of French companies from major 
economic projects. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

