<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   Patten Cites `Confusion' on Right of Abode Issue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK0801080494 Hong Kong SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST in English 8 
Jan 94 p 4 </F>

<F P=103> HK0801080494 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Louis Ng] </F>
  [Text] Governor Chris Patten yesterday said there was 
confusion over China's stance on how Hong Kong residents with 
foreign passports could obtain the right of abode after 1997. 
  "I think that many people in Hong Kong will be a little 
puzzled by the various messages which have been coming out of 
Beijing. 
  "There were, I think, two rather different impressions given 
yesterday about future Chinese intention on right of abode," Mr 
Patten said. 
  The Director of the State Council's Hong Kong and Macao 
Affairs Office, Lu Ping, reportedly said on Thursday morning 
that Hong Kong residents with foreign passports would not need 
to go through another application process to acquire the right 
of abode after 1997. 
  But he said later in the day that people with foreign 
passports would lose their Chinese nationality, and a clear set 
of criteria would be worked out to allow the recovery of 
permanent resident status. 
  Mr Lu added China would adopt a more lenient policy towards 
these people. 
  It is estimated there are 300,000 to 400,000 people whose 
right of abode in Hong Kong will be in doubt after 1997 because 
they own foreign passports. 
  Mr Patten said he was confused about China's stance, and the 
Government was anxious to reach an agreement on the issue to put 
to rest the anxiety of the people involved. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

