<H3> <TI>   `Witnesses' Say Deng Xiaoping Met Chen Yun 11 Jan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1101145394 Tokyo KYODO in English 1441 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1101145394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Shanghai, Jan. 11 KYODO -- China's paramount 
leader Deng Xiaoping met conservative former party leader Chen 
Yun Tuesday [11 January] for about 90 minutes at a hotel here, 
witnesses said. 
  They said Deng, who has reportedly been staying in Shanghai 
since December for relaxation, arrived by car at the hotel where 
Chen, who has often taken a cautious stance toward reform, was 
staying. 
  This was Deng's third reported outing since the 89-year-old 
architect of China's economic reforms moved to the Chinese 
coastal commercial city. 
  Chen, a long-time economic leader and later chief of the 
party's Central Advisory Committee in the 1980s, has been 
staying in the metropolis from around summer last year. 
  A Beijing-funded newspaper in Hong Kong reported Monday that 
Deng had made a rare public appearance on New Year's day, 
visiting a five-star Shanghai hotel and chatting with foreign 
guests. 

</TEXT>

